Quality Hardwood Floor & Stair Refinishing

Every project is different. It requires proper planning, budgeting and the right team to execute your vision. Brian Sexton fulfills all hardwood floor and stair refinishing projects, including everything from antique hardwood floor restoration to gym floor refinishing.

Hardwood Floor Frefinishing

Have your old wood flooring restored to new! We use partial dustless sanding technology to strip the floors of scratches and damage, before applying a stain or seal. Lastly, we add 3 coats of protective waterborne or Swedish surface finish, for that luxury look.

Refinishing Wood Stairs

Treads, risers, stringers, railings and spindles accumulate dirt and oils from constant use, and overtime the finish begins to look old, worn and faded. We can effectively restore these components of your stairway to be looking brand new in no time.

Commercial Wood Floor Refinishing

Give your restaurant, gym or commercial space new life and a refreshed look, by having the hardwood floors professionally refinished. Sanding, staining and protecting the floors will maintain longevity and help elevate the status of any space.

your project has potential

After 10 years, most residential hardwood floors begin showing their age; versus 2 - 3 years for commercial wood floors. Worn finishes, scratches, dullness and discoloration are the most common signs that the wood is due for refinishing. The typical 3/4-inch thick hardwood floor can be sanded 4 - 6 times during its lifetime. So unless you live in a particularly old house, chances are that your wood floors can be restored to a beautiful condition.

HARDWOOD FLOOR MAINTENANCE

Why Refinish Your Floor:

  • - Enhance its longevity and durability
  • - Make the space more liveable while elevating its status
  • - Boost your home's value
  • - Protect it from costly water and moisture damage
  • - Dramatically decrease the number of scratches, dents and imperfections
  • - Provide your floors and stairs with an even color and finish

When to Refinish Your Floor:

  • - You pour a spoonful of water on your floor and it soaks into the wood, rather than form droplets that rest on top of the wood
  • - You start to notice fading, dullness or discoloration of the wood
  • - After water damage or major moisture damage, which causes the boards to cup and / or separate
  • - You notice lots of scratches, dings and dents

How to Care for Your Refinished Floor:

  • - Keep them free of water, dirt, grit and sand
  • - Regularly sweep, swiffer and vacuum
  • - Wash floors with a slightly damp mop using warm water and mild dish soap
  • - Refrain from using wet mops or steam mops, which will damage the finish
  • - Avoid oil or silicone based products, which may be corrosive or abrasive
  • - Avoid vinegar as its acidic nature will break down the finish
